post_text: Starting Wednesday September 16th, there is a change of meal delivery times for the entire district. Times have been adjusted to start 5 minutes later than previously. If you or your child(ren)are unable to reach a stop or get to a school to get a meal, please contact your school’s Family Resource Coordinator who may be able to assist you. If you will be having some else get meals for your child(ren) we do need written permission for them and even for a sibling to be getting your child(ren) meals. You can write us a signed and dated note with the names of the child(ren) receiving meals and whom is in charge to get them or we can get you a form. If there will be a change, please send a new note. Notes can be given to the bus driver or you can send them to the District Office Attn: Ashley Arthur or drop them off there as well. Thank you!

post_text: SDA has announced a waiver to extend the Seamless Summer Program nationwide until December 31, 2020. That means all children in our Neah-Kah-Nie community ages 18 and under, will be able to access meals at no charge. We have added a few new bus routes to reach more of our community children and students. Students do not have to be present to get a meal, their parent can get it for them. Students can get meals for siblings as long as they are 18 and under with proof of parent permission to do so. Each school will provide meals as well from 11:00 a.m. to 12:00 p.m. Meals will include breakfast for the next day and lunch for the same day. We will begin to serve meals on Tuesday, September 8th. Please see the attachments for more information on delivery routes and times.

post_text:
Dylan James and Nicole Bringuel, representing the Tillamook County Face Mask Project and the Tillamook Creamery, delivered 2500 face protectors to the Neah-Kah-Nie School District. These face protectors will be used by kindergarten-12th graders and NKN staff. What an amazing donation! This is approximately 500 hours of volunteer time, in addition to the volunteer hours, the cost to the school district was only $30.
The school district would like to thank the Tillamook County Face Mask Project, Tillamook Creamery, Hurd's Upholstery, Cindy Harrison, Kathleen Walker, Bryn Croty, Anna Mosser, Kelsey Knoble, Betty Diamond Foster, Dylan James Bringuel, Nicole Bringuel, and many others. The craftsmanship, design, and creativity of each face mask is very much appreciated by NKN students and staff.

post_text:
Congratulations Neah-Kah-Nie High School Class of 2020 graduate Danny Vargas! Danny will attend Tillamook Bay Community College in the fall. Danny celebrated his high school graduation with his brother, mother, Socorro and father, Martin.

Danny was Superintendent Paul Erlebach's ASPIRE mentee for two years. ASPIRE is the state of Oregon's mentoring program to help students access education and training beyond high school.

The program matches trained and supportive adult volunteer mentors with middle and high school students to develop a plan to help them meet their future career and education goals. See our impact statewide and check out ASPIREOregon.org to learn more!

CLASS OF 2020
NEAH-KAH-NIE HS GRADUATION
Friday at 11 a.m.
By invitation only. Only guests with tickets will be allowed entrance.

The class of 2020 and High School staff are tremendously thankful for the supportive community we live in.
We will be live streaming graduation on Facebook. Links to the live stream will be emailed to students and parents so they can share, it will also be posted on the district website nknsd.org. The link to the traditional senior slide show will also be posted on the district website.

Thank you to all that can't attend for celebrating with us from a distance.

GGS y NES organizarán reuniones familiares la próxima semana el lunes 17 de agosto de 6:00 p.m. a 7:00 p.m. para que las familias puedan aprender sobre el aprendizaje integral a distancia (CDL)

post_text: The concrete pad for the new 5000 square foot covered outdoor play structure at Nehalem Elementary was poured this week. After the concrete cures for a month, the metal structure will be installed along with new play equipment. Students, staff, parents, and community members are very excited to be able to recreate under a covered, well lit, structure on rainy days. Although the vast majority of the funding for this project came from the school district's general fund, $20,000 came from many years of parent fundraising and generous donations from Nehalem Rural Telecom Inc. (RTI).

Neah-Kah-Nie School District Community, if you have seen First Student buses on local streets, roads, and Hwy 101, without students, bus drivers and volunteers are busy delivering meals to needy students and families during the pandemic. Fortunately, meal deliveries will continue throughout the entire summer thanks to the following collaborative effort of these special volunteers, churches, businesses, and organizations: Bay City United Methodist Church, Nehalem Bay United Methodist Church, Neah-Kah-Nie School District, Mudd Nick Foundation, Fred Meyer, First Student, and a special thank you to Camp Magruder.
This is an example of how the community comes together during times of need to assist one another.
Here is a short video clip describing this effort:
https://www.facebook.com/watch/?v=586245048965715

NKN Class of 2020
Senior Shout-out!
Karissa Hadermann is a 3-year Track and Field Athlete who was district champion in the 100m and 300m hurdles her Junior year, the same year she also placed 6th at state in the 100m hurdles. She had a successful high school FBLA career as well, qualifying for nationals multiple years. She placed 3rd in state for Intro to Business, qualifying and participating at Nationals in Anaheim, Baltimore, and San Antonio, 4th in Hospitality Management, 1st in Organizational Leadership, and was a top 10 in Business Communications and Health Care Administration.
Karissa has maintained a 4.0 GPA in addition to her extracurricular accomplishments!

Senior Shout-out!

Her kind, supportive, and fun demeanor have made her a remarkable co-President for the past two years. Her growth in Graphic Design and technical applications shined this year, earning her a 3rd place finish at FBLA state.

Megan Troutman has grown immensely as a speaker in her four years, to the point where she won first place in Prose at two tournaments in a row this year! Her kind, supportive, and fun demeanor have made her a remarkable co-President for the past two years. There can be no doubt that Megan would have been State-bound this year, and her leadership will be sorely missed! She participated in FBLA throughout high school and this year qualified for nationals. Her growth in Graphic Design and technical applications shined this year, earning her a 3rd place finish at FBLA state.

Senior Shout-out!

Ethan Lee is a 2-year Track and Field Athlete who competed in the hurdles. In Speech and Debate, Ethan Lee qualified for the State competition in Parliamentary Debate with his partner Animesh Patel three years in a row, winning first in the district twice. He also qualified and participated at nationals in San Antonio in FBLA and was a top 10 finisher at state multiple times in his high school career, earning 1st and 3rd in the state of Oregon with his Marketing team.

Ethan is the Valedictorian of the class of 2020.

THANK YOU FROM MR. GERNERT AND THE SMALL ENGINES CLASS!
A huge THANK YOU to the folks that responded to our NKN tools donation drive. The tools and small gas engines that our community has generously donated will allow students to work (safely of course – following online instruction) on disassembling and reassembling an engine at home.
Take home / to go tool kits include: a standard and metric socket set, piston ring compressor, phillips and ¼” hand drivers, feeler gauges, organizational muffin tins and ANSI Z87 safety glasses.
Mr. Gernert has been very pleased with student engagement and these donations will go a long way toward their continued growth as young mechanics. A special thank you to everyone thinking of our students during this challenging time and specifically to the following people:
Bonnie Eberly
Philip Cottle
Jeff Short
Marylynn Marden
DJ Edwards
Greg Hightower

The fencing is going up today so the work can begin on NES’s new covered play area. The new covered area will allow students to get outside rain or shine. The new area is going to come right off the end of the wing along the old playground to double our current play space for students.
We will have a new K-5 play structure, more wall ball and four square, a youth sized half basketball court, and we are hoping to add a Ga Ga Pit later on this fall.
How exciting is this?! Please give a big air hug to any NKN School Board members you see out and about for supporting this amazing new facility so our students can play outside year round!

**Stay tuned for GGS covered play area information...it’s coming soon!

NKN Parents and Students, we are excited to share with you the new supplemental learning page on the school website located on the main page of the website in the parent folder:https://nknsd.org/supplemental-learning/

The term “supplemental educational services” is specific language used by Oregon Department of Education and refers to optional, free academic exposure that is provided to students in various subjects. “Learning support” refers to the services provided to students who need additional help, and it may be used in reference to “enrichment” activities for students to extend their learning. These are not intended to be replacements for school or core curriculum, and it is not initial instruction.

These resources are not required, but available to continue the pursuit of learning.

We hope that many of these activities provided can be done with the family, and that you will have fun in the process of learning!

IMPORTANT MIDDLE SCHOOL INFORMATION

Dear Parents/Guardians of NKN MS students:

Many of you have been asking about picking up contents from your student's lockers as well as workbooks that will be needed for distance learning classes.

We have cleaned out all lockers, placing the contents in plastic bags with your student’s name on it. These bags will be available for pick up, this Thursday, April 9th and Friday, April 10th, from 8am to 4pm both days. Bags are sorted by grade in alphabetical order. The outside door will be open to the MPR so one person may enter at a time to gather their bag, adhering to social distancing protocols.

PS....yes, PE uniforms are included and all library books found in lockers have been turned in to the library.

We look forward to seeing you here on Thursday and Friday!

post_text:
Hello Nehalem Elementary families! We have been busy all week getting supplies and supplementary materials ready for your children.

The pickup dates and times have changed to ONLY Monday April 6th from 10:00 a.m. to 6:00 p.m. Many of you may arrive here at NES at the same time, so please have patience with the limited staff who are working.

When you arrive at the school, please stay in your car and join the regular student drop off/pick up line so we can keep social distancing in place. When you are in line outside of the school, THEN call the school office at 503-355-3650. Give your child's name(s), your child’s teacher(s) and the color and model of the vehicle you are driving. Staff will bring out your child's packet when you get to the front of the line. If you requested to borrow a chromebook, there will be a form to sign, so please bring your own pen. If you are sick, please arrange for someone else to pick up the packet for you.

Thank you in advance for your patience! If you have questions, please call NES today before 4pm.

post_text:
Congrats to Travis Bennett the 2020 2A/1A 195# State Champ!

It is great to see his hard work and dedication pay off. The time in between the two photos consisted of many workouts, practices, matches, miles, wins, and a loss or two. All of which prepared him to achieve his ultimate goal of becoming a state champion.

Great job coaches/parents who have helped Travis along the way: Chris and Renee Bennett, Jon Longfellow, Alejandro Quintana and the Tillamook coaches Lonnie Eggert and Rex Metcalf who have welcomed the Bennett Brothers into their mat club and off season programs/workouts for the last decade.

post_text:
Neah-Kah-Nie Community,

Neah-Kah-Nie School District and the City of Rockaway Beach, are actively pursuing a Safe Routes to Schools Grant. The main purpose of the grant is to improve the safety for cyclists and pedestrians from Rockaway Beach to Neah-Kah-Nie High and Middle Schools. As you are aware, walking, running, and cycling on Highway 101 is not very safe. This grant would provide the necessary funds to address at least some of the school district and City of Rockaway Beach's safety concerns close to the high/middle schools. The link below allows people to comment directly on the plan and provide feedback. The public comment period will run through February 24.

Link to SRTS Plan Public Review Draft: https://rockawaybeach.odotsrtsprojectid.com/

post_text:
Dear NKN High School Parents- today we are sending out 9 week progress reports. Please remember that we staff free after school tutoring 4 days per week (not Fridays). With only 3 weeks to go in the trimester, now is the time to take advantage of the extra academic support. In order to be eligible for sports students must be passing 4 out of 5 classes. In order to participate in school sponsored field trips, students must be passing all of their classes, they also need to be in good standing with behavior and attendance.
If you are curious about your student's grades, you can always refer to our online system "Parent View" please contact the school office if you need assistance with your account.
503-355-2272

NES Families:
Each month schools do safety drills to practice for emergencies. Today we did a school-wide Lock Down drill. It can be difficult to prepare students and staff for these situations and not scare them. We tried very hard today to be honest, yet general enough to not leave our students fearful. Please talk to your children about our drill today. Ask them what they practiced. If you have any questions please call your child’s teacher or me. -Ms. Woika

post_text: NKN Pirate Historians and Enthusiasts...your input is requested as we work to update our " brand" We are interested in collecting historical Pirate artifacts, jerseys, logos, flags, posters etc... our goal is twofold. We want to preserve our pirate history in a new hall of fame (currently in the planning phase) and we want to be ready to embrace a new, consistent pirate logo that we will use on our walls, floors and pirate gear next year and into the future. Please send pictures, ideas, suggestions to heidib@nknsd.org.

HAPPY FRIDAY PIRATE FAMILIES AND FRIENDS!

We have a home football game tonight against the Nestucca Bobcats, we are looking forward to seeing our fans and a great matchup.

Game time is 7 p.m. come a little early to get a seat in the grandstands and for some great food provided by our Senior Safe group.

Tickets $6 Adults, $4 for students without student body card and senior citizens. NKN students with student body cards get in for free.

$500- Captain's Club
$1000-Pirate's Club
For more information about sponsorship, ask at the gate at tonight's game!

Neah-Kah-Nie is a smoke, vape, tobacco free environment- please respect our students, staff, athletes, community members and facilities by refraining while on or within 1000 feet of district property.

post_text: NKN Parents and Community, Leo Lawyer accepted the Cleveland High School Principal position for Portland Public Schools. Leo was the NKN High School Athletic Director for two years and served as the NKN Middle School Principal for seven years. The Neah-Kah-Nie School District is excited for Leo as he transitions to a high school leadership role. The school district would like to thank Principal Lawyer for his many years of outstanding service to the school district and to the community. Under Leo’s leadership, Neah-Kah-Nie Middle School has a reputation where students are challenged and supported. Thank you Leo!

post_text: NKN Staff, Parents and Community, I am very excited to introduce Lori Dilbeck as the new Neah-Kahk-Nie Middle School Principal! Lori has 25 years of successful experience as an educator. She served as the Tri City Elementary Principal, for the South Umpqua School District, from 2015-19. As many of you know, Lori was an outstanding Neah-Kah-Nie School District classroom teacher/literacy coach for seventeen years. Lori earned her Oregon Initial Administrator License from Portland State University. She has a Master of Education in Curriculum & Instruction and a Bachelor of Science in Elementary Education. As an instructional leader, Lori believes, "Building leadership capacity at Neah-Kah-Nie Middle School is the key to increasing academic achievement." Welcome back to Neah-Kah-Nie School District Lori!

post_text:
Everyone is invited to the dedication of the Jim Mudd Field at the Neah-Kah-Nie School District main office in Rockaway, Friday, May 31 at 6:30 p.m. Neah-Kah-Nie Youth Athletics, with the support of many local volunteers, including funding from the Mudd Nick Foundation, was instrumental in renovating the athletic field. Please join the Mudd family, Mudd Nick Foundation board members, Neah-Kah-Nie Youth Athletics, and the Neah-Kah-Nie School District in recognizing Jim Mudd, co-founder of the Mudd Nick Foundation, for his many years of service to provide learning experiences that stimulate children to aspire to their greatest potential and to pursue their dreams.
For more information on the Mudd Nick Foundation muddnickfoundation.org
The Mudd Nick Foundation's second largest fundraiser, The Nehalem Bay Crab Derby, hosted by Kellys Brighton Marina, is June 1 from 9:00-5:00 pm, please support the Mudd Nick Foundation.

post_text:
Neah-Kah-Nie High School Kindness Week-
February 25-March 1.

Donation Drive- Tuesday we are collecting clean clothes including warm jackets, new socks etc.
Wednesday we are collecting Toiletries including shampoo, deodorant, toothpaste and tooth brushes.
Thursday we are collecting blankets, sleeping bags, tents, backpacks, and new toys for children.
Friday we are collecting non-perishable food items (boxed and canned foods)

We invite our community to join us- you may bring donations to the HS office if you would like to participate!

Also during this week, we are encouraging random acts of kindness, recognition and appreciation!

post_text: On Friday, January 18th, Neah-Kah-Nie Middle and High School teachers received training in Talented and Gifted (TAG) education. Angela Allen, TAG Educational Specialist with the Oregon Department of Education, trained the teachers on the TAG identification process, common characteristics of students eligible for TAG, and writing course instructional TAG plans that address the rate and level of learning for students. Angela will be returning this spring to train elementary teachers.

Yesterday, Parent Council brought their Glitter Bug machine to NES and taught kids why it’s important to thoroughly wash their hands. Kids applied special Glitter Bug lotion, looked at their hands under the machine, washed, then looked again. Parts of their hands that weren’t washed well glowed and glowed with Glitter Bugs!
Thank you, Denise Weiss and Nola Angela Smith!! We appreciate you!!

post_text:
Middle School News: last Friday we held our first TAG event through onsite Saturday Academy titled, "Sea Life Dissection." Students explored through dissection activities the inner-workings of marine life of all kinds, and how to work in groups. "I loved learning about how different parts of a squid help it navigate through the water, and hypothesizing how each part of the animal helps it ward off attackers in the wild. It was SO AWESOME!

We would like to thank the good people at the Mudd Nick Foundation for supporting this activity, and for all they do to expand the minds of all young people in our school district.
Mr. Lawyer~Principal

The Eugene Schmuck Foundation is a BIG community partner of the Neah-Kah-Nie School District. Here is information on its fundraiser:

The Eugene Schmuck Foundation's first fundraiser is just around the corner! Please join us at the Big Wave Cafe, Thursday, January 17, from 5:00-7:30pm.

The Big Wave Cafe has graciously donated a spaghetti dinner including salad, dessert and coffee/soda. Beer and wine will be available for purchase. Tickets are $15 and all proceeds will be used toward scholarships and support for our local community. You can purchase tickets online, from a ESF board member or at the door. We also urge you to follow us on Facebook and RSVP to our Facebook Event.

Looking forward to seeing you this Thursday!

post_text:
The FIRST LEGO League qualifying tournament on Saturday December 8th at Intel was challenging to say the least.
Our six teams came to competition to show off the work they did this Fall and left a little more knowledgeable about how much dedication it takes to compete against incredible Willamette Valley teams that eat, sleep, and breathe this competition. It was a fun day in spite of the early realization that we were not as developed as the teams we competed against. We were asked, "How big is your school?" when we replied that our school had 200 students the response inevitably was, "We have 1000 students at our school, and we are the only team from our school!"
We were lucky to provide so many NKN students with access to this competition, and so many came away with thoughtful insights that have already informed our process moving forward to next year.
Many thanks to our sponsors ODE, ORTOP, Uppercrust Pizza, and the Mudd Nick Foundation as well as our many volunteers and mentors for the teams. This season couldn't have happened without you all!

post_text:
Today was a special day for Tracy DeGandi's fourth grade class at Nehalem Elementary. Bucky Buckwalter, former Portland Trail Blazer Vice President of Basketball Operations, NBA Executive of the Year Award recipient, NBA coach, and inductee of the Oregon Sports Hall of Fame, visited Mr. DeGandi's class on behalf of the Mudd Nick Foundation. Bucky shared with students highlights from his long history with the Trail Blazers, playing high school basketball at La Grande High School, and the importance of a high quality education.
Students thanked Bucky for organizing countless Mudd Nick Foundation sponsored trips for students and staff to watch the Portland Trail Blazers. Students presented Bucky with a Neah-Kah-Nie High School sweatshirt.
Bucky added to Mr. DeGandi's collection of Trail Blazer memorabilia with a gift of two team photos from the 1990's.

Neah-Kah-Nie School District Community, I am sorry to announce Jim Mudd, co-founder of the Mudd Nick Foundation, passed away Monday, October 1.
Jim's charisma, engaging personality, sense of humor, honesty, business acumen, faith, organizational skills, leadership, boundless energy, and relentless advocate for children, were his outstanding traits.
Jim was a devoted father, grandfather, and husband.
Jim's commitment to providing life changing opportunities for North County children through the Mudd Nick Foundation is his legacy.
Neah-Kah-Nie School District students and staff will deeply miss Jim Mudd.

post_text:
NEAH-KAH-NIE SCHOOL DISTRICT BOARD OF DIRECTORS ANNOUNCES BOARD VACANCY

Neah-Kah-Nie School District Board of Directors has just announced a vacancy in Zone 5 which shares a common boundary with Zone 6.
This zone has a common boundary with zone 6 and includes the areas of the Twin Rocks, West Garibaldi and East Garibaldi precincts except for that area of the Twin Rocks precinct which lies in Zones 3 & 4.
The board will exercise its normal process of posting the opening for 20 days, take applications, conduct interviews and appoint someone to this position. You may contact the Tillamook County Clerk’s office at 503-842-3402 to verify that your address falls within the correct zone. The requirements for serving on the school board are that you must be a registered voter, have lived within the district for one year, and be a resident in the zone from which the vacancy has occurred. For an application please contact Kathie Sellars at 503-355-3506.

post_text: In addition to the district-wide Retirement Celebration that was held yesterday, NKN Middle School hosted our own little shindig for our dear Karla Watkins Wednesday. Although she will be missed by all district employees when she retires at the end of the summer, the middle school and its student body will deeply miss Karla come September. Her infectious smile, laugh, and hard-working work ethic is one for all to emulate. We love you, Karla!
